Cell.Data: This spreadsheet is used to support the definition of resources or data types (structures). A complete set of instructions on the various tabs, columns and rules associated with populating this spreadsheet can be found here:
The detailed description of a substance, typically at a level beyond what is used for prescribing
Identifier by which this substance is known
High level categorization, e.g. polymer or nucleic acid
Status of substance within the catalogue e.g. approved
If the substance applies to only human or veterinary use
Textual comment about this record of a substance
Role that the moiety is playing
Identifier by which this moiety substance is known
Textual name for this moiety substance
General specifications for this substance, including how it is related to other substances
A category for this property, e.g. Physical, Chemical, Enzymatic
Property type e.g. viscosity, pH, isoelectric point
Parameters that were used in the measurement of a property (e.g. for viscosity: measured at 20C with a pH of 7.1)
A substance upon which a defining property depends (e.g. for solubility: in water, in alcohol)
Specified per moiety according to the Hill system, i.e. first C, then H, then alphabetical, each moiety separated by a dot
Applicable for single substances that contain a radionuclide or a non-natural isotopic ratio
Substance identifier for each non-natural or radioisotope
Substance name for each non-natural or radioisotope
The type of isotopic substitution present in a single substance
Half life - for a non-natural nuclide
The molecular weight or weight range (for proteins, polymers or nucleic acids)
The method by which the molecular weight was determined
Type of molecular weight such as exact, average (also known as. number average), weight average

Used to capture quantitative values for a variety of elements. If only limits are given, the arithmetic mean would be the average. If only a single definite value for a given element is given, it would be captured in this field
The molecular weight or weight range (for proteins, polymers or nucleic acids)
The type of structure (e.g. Full, Partial, Representative)
The structural representation as text string in a format e.g. InChI, SMILES, MOLFILE, CDX
An attached file with the structural representation
The date at which the code status is changed as part of the terminology maintenance
Any comment can be provided in this field, if necessary
If this is the preferred name for this substance
The use context of this name for example if there is a different name a drug active ingredient as opposed to a food colour additive
The jurisdiction where this name applies
Details of the official nature of this name
Which authority uses this official name
The status of the official name
The molecular weight or weight range (for proteins, polymers or nucleic acids)
A link between this substance and another, with details of the relationship
A pointer to another substance, as a resource or just a representational code
For example "salt to parent", "active moiety", "starting material"
For example where an enzyme strongly bonds with a particular substance, this is a defining relationship for that enzyme, out of several possible substance relationships
A numeric factor for the relationship, for instance to express that the salt of a substance has some percentage of the active substance in relation to some other
An operator for the amount, for example "average", "approximately", "less than"
Data items specific to nucleic acids
Material or taxonomic/anatomical source for the substance
